==English==
===Etymology===
[[Old English]] ''&aelig;ghwe&thorn;er'', a combination meaning "any - whether"

===Pronunciation===
*(''especially American and Australian''; ''also British''): &#275;''th''&#601;(r), /i&#720;ð&#601;(r)/, /<tt>i:D@</tt>(<tt>r</tt>)/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-iːðə(r)|Rhymes: -iːðə(r)]]
*(''British and Canadian''; ''also Australian''): &#299;''th''&#601;(r), /a&#618;ð&#601;(r)/, /<tt>aID@</tt>(<tt>r</tt>)/
*:[[Rhymes:English:-aɪðə(r)|Rhymes: -aɪðə(r)]]

===Adjective===
'''either''' (''not [[comparable]]'')

#One or other of two.
#:''I don't mind whether your mother or father attends - you can bring either parent.''
#Each of two; [[both]] (''used with a singular noun'')
#:''The room has a door at either end.''

====Translations====
*French: (2): [[chaque]]
*Italian: (2): [[ciascuno]]

===Pronoun===
'''either'''

#One or the other of two.
#:''I don't mind whether your mother or father attends - you can bring either.''

====Translations====
*French: [[l'un ou l'autre]] ''m'', l'une ou l'autre ''f'' (''for two feminine nouns'')
*Italian: [[l'uno o l'altro]] ''m'', l'una o l'altra ''f''  (''for two feminine nouns'')

===Adverb===
'''either'''

#Too (''after a negative'').
#:''I don't like him and I don't like her either.''

*French: [[non plus]]
*Italian: [[neanche]], [[nemmeno]], [[neppure]]

===Conjunction===
'''either'''

#Introduces the first of two options, the second of which is introduced by [[or]].
#:''Either you eat your dinner or you go to your room.''

====Translations====
*French: [[ou]]
*Italian: [[o#Italian|o]], [[oppure]]

===Usage note===
*'''Either''' is used when there are two alternatives.  When there are more than two, [[any]] is used instead.

